Compiling HTML to LaTeX with CSS
Manuel Serrano,
speaker Cyprien Nicolas
Inria Mditerranne
HopTeX
<HOPTEX>
HopTeX
  • A batch authoring system
  • Documents are programs
  • Produces either HTML or LaTeX
Background
  • HTML as a Scheme datatype
    (DSSSL'96, LAML'99)
  • HTML as a datatype
    (XDuce'00, XQuery'07)
  • Documents as Scheme programs
    (S[ck]ribe'02, Scribble'09)
What's New?
  • Based on Hop
  • Relies on Web technologies (DOM, CSS)
  • A multi-tier application
  • A lightweight wiki syntax
  • Idiosynchrasys agnosism
A Brief Intro. to Hop
A multi-tier programming language
(for the web)
Multi-tier programming
  • Server-side is compiled to native code
  • Server programs elaborate ASTs
  • ASTs are compiled to HTML+JavaScript
A Hop Program
(define-service (hello n)
  (let ((1..n (iota n 1)))
    (<HTML>
      (<TABLE>
        (<TR> (<TH>) (map <TH> 1..n))
        (map (lambda (i)
               (<TR>
                 (<TH> i)
                 (map (lambda (j)
                        (<TD> :onclick ~(alert (+ $j $i))
                          (* j i)))
                  1..n)))
          1..n)))))


http://localhost:8080/hop/hello?n=10

,(<STRONG> (<TT> [anyhow])).])

Deep Syntax/Surface Syntax
  • Wiki (surface) -> Hop (deep): ,(
  • Hop -> Wiki: <WIKI>
The //deep// escape sequence is ,(<Q> (<TT> ",(")). It can 
be used to insert HTML trees such as ,(<KBD> "C-x s"). 
The ++<WIKI>++ markup is used to 
,(<SPAN> :style "color: #157580"
   (<WIKI> [enter the //surface// syntax from the 
//deep// syntax])).
=>
The deep escape sequence is ,(. It can be used to insert HTML trees such as C-x s. The <WIKI> markup is used to enter the surface syntax from the deep syntax.
LaTeX
<LATEX>
HTML vs LaTeX
  • Observation 1: LaTeX and HTML have many similarities
  • <EM>foo</EM> ≈ \emph{foo}
  • Observation 2: LaTeX and HTML are not isomorphic
  • <TABLE><TR><TD><TABLE>...</TABLE></TD></TR></TABLE>
  • Observation 3: CSS almost compiles
CSS Compilation
  • The source example:
    (<WIKI> [Hop supports **strong**
//emphasize// and ++mono space++.
These can be **//combined//**
**++anyhow++**.])
  • + an ad-hoc CSS file:
    strong:before { content: "{\\textbf{"; }
em:before { content: "{\\emph{"; }
strong:after, em:after { content: "}}"; }
  • =>
    Hop supports {\textbf{strong}}
{\emph{emphasize}} and {\texttt{mono space}}.
These can be {\textbf{\emph{combined}}}
{\textbf{\texttt{anyhow}}}.
CSS Driven Compilation
  • Server-side CSS processing (HSS'10)
  • A new @media rule:
    @media tex {
  strong:before {
    content: "{\\textbf{";
  }
  ...
  sub:before {
    content: "$_{\\mbox{\\scriptsize{";
  }
  sub:after {
    content: "}}}$";
  }
  ...
}
3 Special Cases
<IMG>, <PRE>, and <TABLE>
  • A case study, an image:
    {{screenshot.png|a screenshot}}
     
    img { width: 80%; }
  • =>
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\linewidth]{screenshot.png}
IMG
  • A new CSS attribute:
    @media tex {
  img { proc: $xml->tex-img; }
}
  • An ad-hoc compiler:
    (define (xml->tex-img node::xml-img css p)
  (fprintf p "\\includegraphics[width=~a]{~a}"
     (let ((w (node-computed-style node :width css)))
       (if (string? w)
           (let ((m (pregexp-match "^([0-9]+)%$" w)))
              (if (not m)
                  w
                  (format "0.~a\\linewidth" (cadr m))))
           "\\linewidth"))
     (dom-get-attribute node "src")))

Example 1: BibTeX
  • A Full BibTeX parser in Hop
    @Book{knuth:tex86, author = {Knuth, D.}, title = {The TEXbook,}, publisher = {Addison-Wesley, Readings}, address = {Massachusetts, USA}, year = {1986}, volume = {A}, series = {Computers and Typesetting}, }
  • Wiki bibliographic entries:
    [[bib://knuth:86 lamport:latex86]]
The Bibliography
  • Bibiographic entry predicate
    (define (citation? e::xml-element)
  (with-access::xml-element e (attributes)
    (let ((href (xml-get-attribute :href attributes)))
      (when href
        (let ((val (xml-attribute-value href)))
          (and (string? val)
               (string-prefix? "bib://" val)))))))
  • Filtering bibliographic entries
    (define (dom-get-citations doc)
  (filter citation? (dom-get-elements-by-tag-name doc "a")))
Example 2: Floats
Controlling the placement of floats in LaTeX
@media tex {
  #float1 {
    width: 100%;
    column-count: 2;
    float: -350;
  }
}
Moving floats
(define (move-float-backward! node offset)
  (let loop ((o offset)
	     (prev node))
    (if (= o 0)
	(dom-insert-before! (dom-parent-node prev) node prev)
	(loop (- o 1) (dom-previous-node prev doc)))))

(define (dom-previous-node node doc)
  (let ((sibling (dom-previous-sibling node)))
    (if (not sibling)
	(dom-parent-node node)
	(dom-last-node sibling))))
